<TITLE>Sloan was right on Anthem and Kaeperneck</TITLE>


<TEXT>
In a recent Letter-to-the-Editor <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">appearing</EVENT> on <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE" value="2017-01-29">Sunday, Jan. 15</TIMEX3>, Daniel J. Andrews from The Villages <EVENT eid="e2" class="REPORTING">stated</EVENT> that Russ Sloan <EVENT eid="e3" class="I_STATE">needs</EVENT> a history lesson. No, it is Mr. Andrews that needs a lesson on our Constitution and the First Amendment. 
 
In the <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE">column</EVENT> by Russ Sloan regarding 49ers quarterback ColinKaeperneck not <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">standing</EVENT> for the National Anthem, Mr. Sloan <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">pointed</EVENT> out that while Mr. Kaeperneck has the right to <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">do</EVENT> that as an individual, that right does not exist if your employer, the 49ers, does not <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE">approve</EVENT>. First Amendment rights are not the same as an employee as they are as an individual. We <EVENT eid="e9" class="STATE">have</EVENT> freedom of speech, but an employer can <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE">take</EVENT> action against an employee who <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE">uses</EVENT> vulgar or obscene <EVENT eid="e12" class="OCCURRENCE">language</EVENT> with a customer or coworker. Legally, ColinKaeperneck does not have the right to protest standing for our National Anthem unless his employer <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE">approves</EVENT>. Russ Sloan simply <EVENT eid="e14" class="I_ACTION">pointed</EVENT> out that if he was the head football coach of the 49ers, he would privately <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">let</EVENT> the ownership <EVENT eid="e16" class="I_STATE">know</EVENT> that either Kaeperneck stands for the National Anthem or the 49ers can <EVENT eid="e17" class="OCCURRENCE">find</EVENT> a new coach or a new quarterback. 
 
It is clear that Mr. Andrews does not fully <EVENT eid="e18" class="OCCURRENCE">understand</EVENT> the limits of the First Amendment as an individual versus as an employee. The ownership of the 49ers, for whatever reason, <EVENT eid="e19" class="I_ACTION">chose</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e20" class="OCCURRENCE">tolerate</EVENT> Kaeperneck's disrespect of our National Anthem. Apparently Mr. Andrews feels the same way. Mr. Sloan <EVENT eid="e21" class="OCCURRENCE">felt</EVENT> differently and his position was 100 percent correct based on our Constitution and the limitations of the First Amendment rights in the workplace. Russ Sloan does not need a lesson on American history, Mr. Andrews <EVENT eid="e22" class="I_STATE">needs</EVENT> a lesson on our Constitution! 
 
Don Van Beck 
 
Tavares
</TEXT>


